"To ensure 100% data integrity, I implemented an iterative ETL script. I utilized the DROP TABLE command to allow for a repeatable build process. During the transformation, I introduced a RowID to act as a surrogate key, which provided a unique identifier missing from the raw source data.

To validate the success of the cleaning process, I performed a relational JOIN between the Staging and Production layers. This audit verified that the conditional logic successfully converted 100% of the non-standard 'NULL' strings into numeric identifiers (0) while maintaining a strict 1:1 relationship between the raw and processed records."

Summary of the "Why"
You aren't just running it to fix the data again—you are running it to re-build the table correctly with an ID so that you can prove to your professor that your code didn't make any mistakes. It's the difference between saying "I fixed it" and showing a receipt that proves it.

